The '''DGP model''' is a model of [[gravity]] proposed by [[Gia Dvali]], [[Gregory Gabadadze]], and [[Massimo Porrati]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gia Dvali |author2=Gregory Gabadadze |author3=Massimo Porrati | title=4D gravity on a brane in 5D Minkowski space | year = 2000 | journal = Physics Letters | volume=B485 | issue=1–3 | pages=208–214 | arxiv=hep-th/0005016 | doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(00)00669-9|bibcode = 2000PhLB..485..208D }}</ref> The model is popular among some [[model building (particle physics)|model builders]], but has resisted being embedded into [[string theory]].
==Overview== The DGP model assumes the existence of a 4+1-dimensional [[Minkowski space]], within which ordinary 3+1-dimensional Minkowski space is embedded. The model assumes an [[action (physics)|action]] consisting of two terms: One term is the usual [[Einstein–Hilbert action]], which involves only the 4-D [[spacetime]] dimensions. The other term is the equivalent of the Einstein–Hilbert action, as extended to all 5 dimensions. The 4-D term dominates at short distances, and the 5-D term dominates at long distances.
The model was proposed in part in order to reproduce the [[cosmic acceleration]] of [[dark energy]] without any need for a small but non-zero [[vacuum energy]] density. But critics<ref>{{cite journal | first = Dimitry | last = Gorbunov |author2=Koyama, Kazuya |author3=Sibiryakov, Sergei | year = 2006 | title = More on ghosts in the Dvali-Gabadaze-Porrati model | bibcode = 2006PhRvD..73d4016G | journal = Physical Review | volume =D73 | issue = 4 | pages = 044016 | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevD.73.044016|arxiv = hep-th/0512097 }}</ref> argue that this branch of the theory is unstable. However, the theory remains interesting because of Dvali's claim that the unusual structure of the graviton [[propagator]] makes non-perturbative effects important in a seemingly linear regime, such as the solar system. Because there is no four-dimensional, linearized [[effective field theory|effective theory]] that reproduces the DGP model for weak-field gravity, the theory avoids the [[vDVZ discontinuity]] that otherwise plagues attempts to write down a theory of massive gravity.
In 2008, Fang ''et al.'' argued that recent cosmological observations (including measurements of [[baryon acoustic oscillations]] by the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]], and measurements of the [[cosmic microwave background]] and [[type 1a supernovae]]) is in direct conflict with the DGP cosmology<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Wenjuan Fang |author2=Sheng Wang |author3=Wayne Hu |author4=Zoltán Haiman |author5=Lam Hui |author6=Morgan May | title=Challenges to the DGP model from horizon-scale growth and geometry | year = 2008 | journal = Physical Review | volume=D78 | issue=10 | pages=103509 | arxiv=0808.2208 | doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.78.103509|bibcode = 2008PhRvD..78j3509F }}</ref> unless a [[cosmological constant]] or some other form of dark energy is added.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Lucas Lombriser |author2=Wayne Hu |author3=Wenjuan Fang |author4=Uroš Seljak | title=Cosmological constraints on DGP braneworld gravity with brane tension | year = 2009 | journal = Physical Review | volume=D80 | issue=6 | pages=063536 | arxiv=0905.1112 | doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.80.063536|bibcode = 2009PhRvD..80f3536L }}</ref> However, this negates the appeal of the DGP cosmology, which accelerates without needing to add dark energy.
==See also== * [[Kaluza–Klein theory]] * [[Randall–Sundrum model]] * [[Large extra dimension]]
