{{Infobox artist |name = Emily Willoughby |nationality = American |education = |alma_mater = [[Thomas Edison State University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.isironline.org/2017-isir-prize-for-best-student-paper-emily-willoughby/ |title=2017 ISIR Prize for Best Student Paper: Emily Willoughby |website=Intelligence |publisher=International Society for Intelligence Research |date=July 27, 2017 |accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref> |known_for = [[Paleoart]], illustration |website = {{URL|https://emilywilloughby.com/}} }} [[File:Dakotaraptor wiki.jpg|thumb|''[[Dakotaraptor]]'' by Emily Willoughby]]
'''Emily Willoughby''' is an American [[paleoart]]ist, illustrator, writer, and PhD student in [[behavior genetics]] living in [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite book|last = Terakado | first = Kazuo | title = The Art of the Dinosaur | publisher = PIE International | date = 2017 | pages = 159–177| isbn = 978-4756249227}}</ref> Willoughby is best known for specializing in illustrating [[maniraptoran]] [[dinosaur]]s, although she has also done illustrations of [[ceratopsian]] dinosaurs and [[ankylosauria]]ns for the nonprofit Institute for the Study of Mongolian Dinosaurs.<ref>{{cite web| title = Institute for the Study of Mongolian Dinosaurs| url = https://mongoliandinosaurs.org/learn-more/mongolian-dinosaurs/ | access-date = December 8, 2017}}</ref>
Willoughby is noted for her interest in birds, [[dromaeosaurids]] and other feathered animals.<ref>{{cite book|last = White | first = Steve | title = Dinosaur Art II | publisher = Titan Books | pages = 42–57 | date = 2017 | isbn = 978-1785653988}}</ref> She has done illustrations of many feathered [[theropod]]s for scientific papers, most notably of ''[[Dakotaraptor steini]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = DePalma | first1 = Robert A. |display-authors=etal | year = 2015 | title = The First Giant Raptor (Theropoda: Dromaeosauridae) from the Hell Creek Formation | url = https://kuscholarworks.ku.edu/bitstream/handle/1808/18764/DePalma%2014.pdf | journal = Paleontological Contributions | volume = | issue = 14| pages = 1–16| doi = 10.17161/paleo.1808.18764}}</ref>
Willoughby, along with Jonathan Kane, T. Michael Keesey, Glenn Morton and James Comer, also authored ''God's Word or Human Reason?'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Spence|first1=Steven|title=Book Review: God's Word or Human Reason?|url=https://www.gotscience.org/2017/02/book-review-gods-word-human-reason/|website=GotScience.org|date=14 February 2017}}</ref> a 2017 book detailing the [[relationship between religion and science]], in which the authors argue that there is no need for a Christian lifestyle to be incompatible with scientific consensus. Many of the authors talk about their former [[creationist]] lifestyles and beliefs throughout the book.<ref name=“GWoHR”>{{cite book | last1 = Kane | first1 = Jonathan | last2 = Willoughby | first2 = Emily | last3 = Keesey | first3 = T. Michael | title = God's Word or Human Reason? | publisher = Inkwater Press | date = 2017 | isbn = 978-1629013725}}</ref>
Willoughby's art is mentioned and featured commonly in various programs and dinosaur books, such as Paul Barrett and [[Darren Naish]]'s ''Dinosaurs: How They Lived and Evolved 2016''.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Naish | first1 = Darren | last2 = Barrett | first2 = Paul | title = Dinosaurs: How They Lived and Evolved | publisher = The Natural History Museum | date = 2016 | isbn = 978-0565093112}}</ref>
