The generative approach to [[second-language acquisition|second language (L2) acquisition]] applies theoretical insights developed from within [[generative linguistics]] to investigate how second languages are learned by adults and children.  Research is conducted in [[syntax]], [[phonology]], [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphology]], [[phonetics]] and [[semantics]].

The main questions in generative second language acquisition include whether [[Universal grammar|Universal Grammar]] is available to the adult second language learner to guide acquisition, as it is to the first language learner; whether second language learners can reset [[Principles and parameters|linguistic parameters]]; whether second-language learners experience difficulties [[Interface hypothesis|interfacing between different modules]] of the grammar; and whether child second language acquisition differs from that of adults. As generative second language research endeavors to explain the totality of L2 acquisition phenomena, it is also concerned with investigating the extent of [[Language transfer|linguistic transfer]], [[Critical period hypothesis|maturational effects]] on acquisition, and why some learners [[Interlanguage fossilization|fail to acquire]] a target-like L2 grammar even with abundant input.

Research in generative second-language acquisition is presented at a range of conferences, including:  GASLA ([[Generative Approaches to Second Language Acquisition]]), GALANA ([[Generative Approaches to Language Acquisition]] - North America), and BUCLD ([[Boston University Conference on Language Development]]).

Prominent researchers of the topic include [[Suzanne Flynn]] of [[MIT]], [[Bonnie Schwartz]] of [[University of Hawaii]], [[Antonella Sorace]] of [[University of Edinburgh]], and [[Lydia White]] of [[McGill University]].

