{{term|[[black body]]}}
{{defn|A hypothetical idealized physical body that completely absorbs all incident {{gli|electromagnetic radiation}}, regardless of {{gli|frequency}} or {{gli|angle of incidence}}. Perfect black bodies are imagined as substitutes for actual physical bodies in many theoretical discussions of {{gli|thermodynamics}}, and the construction of nearly perfect black bodies in the real world remains a topic of interest for materials engineers. Contrast ''{{gli|white body}}''.}}
{{term|[[black-body radiation]]}}
{{defn|The type of electromagnetic radiation within or surrounding a body in thermodynamic equilibrium with its environment, or emitted by a {{gli|black body}} (an opaque and non-reflective body) held at constant, uniform temperature. The radiation has a specific spectrum and intensity that depends only on the temperature of the body.}}
{{term|[[block and tackle]]}}
{{defn|A system of two or more {{gli|pulley|pulleys}} with a rope or cable threaded between them, usually used to lift or pull heavy loads.}}
{{term|[[Bohr model]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[boiling point]]}}
{{defn|The {{gli|temperature}} at which a {{gli|liquid}} undergoes a phase change into a {{gli|gas}}; the vapour pressure of liquid and gas are equal at this temperature.}}
{{term|[[boiling point elevation]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[Boltzmann constant]]}}
{{defn|A physical constant relating the average {{gli|kinetic energy}} of the particles in a {{gli|gas}} with the {{gli|temperature}} of the gas. It is the gas constant R divided by the Avogadro constant NA.}}
{{term|[[Bose–Einstein condensate]] (BEC)}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[boson]]}}
{{defn|A type of {{gli|particle}} that behaves according to [[Bose–Einstein statistics]] and possesses integer {{gli|spin}}. Bosons include {{gli|elementary particle|elementary particles}} such as {{gli|photon|photons}}, {{gli|gluon|gluons}}, {{gli|W and Z bosons}}, {{gli|Higgs boson|Higgs bosons}}, and the hypothetical {{gli|graviton}}, as well as certain {{gli|composite particle|composite particles}} such as {{gli|meson|mesons}} and {{gli|stable nuclide|stable nuclides}} of even {{gli|mass number}}. Bosons constitute one of two main classes of particles, the other being {{gli|fermion|fermions}}. Unlike fermions, there is no limit to the number of bosons that can occupy the same {{gli|quantum state}}.}}
{{term|[[Boyle's law]]}}
{{defn|The volume of a given mass of a gas at constant temperature is inversely proportional to the pressure.}}
{{term|[[Bra–ket notation]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[Bragg's law]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[bremsstrahlung]]}}
{{defn|Radiation emitted by the {{gli|acceleration}} of unbound charged particles.}}
{{term|[[Brewster's angle]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[british thermal unit]] (btu)}}
{{defn|An Imperial unit of {{gli|energy}} defined as the amount of energy needed to heat one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit; 1 btu is equal to about 1055 {{gli|joule|joules}}. In scientific contexts the btu has largely been replaced by the SI unit of energy, the joule.}}
{{term|[[brittleness]]}}
{{defn|The tendency of a material to break without significant {{gli|plasticity|plastic}} {{gli|deformation}} when subjected to {{gli|stress}}. Brittle materials absorb relatively little energy prior to fracture, even those of high strength. Breaking is often accompanied by a snapping sound.}}
{{term|[[Brownian motion]]}}
{{ghat|Also called '''pedesis'''.}}
{{defn|The presumably random movement of particles suspended in a fluid (liquid or gas) resulting from their bombardment by the fast-moving atoms or molecules in the gas or liquid.}}
{{term|[[Bulk modulus]]}}
{{defn|A measure of a substance's resistance to uniform compression defined as the ratio of the infinitesimal pressure increase to the resulting relative decrease of the volume. Its base unit is the {{gli|pascal}}.}}
{{term|[[buoyancy]]}}
{{defn|An upward {{gli|force}} exerted by a fluid that opposes the weight of an immersed object.}}
{{glossaryend}}

