==R==

{{glossary}}
{{term|[[radiant energy]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[radiation]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[radioactive decay]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[radionuclide]]}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''radioactive nuclide''', '''radioisotope''', or '''radioactive isotope'''.}}
{{defn|Any {{gli|nuclide}} possessing excess nuclear energy to the point that it is unstable. Such excess energy is emitted through any of several processes of {{gli|radioactive decay}}, resulting in a {{gli|stable nuclide}} or sometimes another unstable radionuclide which can then undergo further decay. Certain radionuclides can occur naturally; many others can be produced artificially in [[nuclear reactor]]s, {{gli|cyclotron|cyclotrons}}, {{gli|particle accelerator|particle accelerators}}, or radionuclide generators.}}
{{term|[[Radius of curvature (optics)|radius of curvature]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[redshift]]}}
{{defn|A phenomenon which occurs when {{gli|light}} seen coming from an object that is moving away is proportionally increased in {{gli|wavelength}} or "shifted" to the red end of the {{gli|visible light}} spectrum.}}
{{term|[[refraction]]}}
{{defn|The change in direction of a {{gli|wave}} as it passes from one {{gli|transmission medium}} to another or as a result of a gradual change in the medium. Though most commonly used in the context of refraction of {{gli|light}}, other waves such as {{gli|sound}} waves and [[wind wave|fluid waves]] also experience refraction.}}
{{term|[[refractive index]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[relative atomic mass]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[relativistic mechanics]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[rigid body]]}}
{{defn|An idealization of a solid body in which {{gli|deformation}} is neglected. In other words, the distance between any two given points of a rigid body remains constant in time regardless of the external forces exerted on it. Even though such an object cannot physically exist due to relativity, objects can normally be assumed to be perfectly rigid if they are not moving near the {{gli|speed of light}}.}}
{{term|[[rotational energy]]}}
{{ghat|Also called '''angular kinetic energy'''.}}
{{defn|The {{gli|kinetic energy}} due to the rotation of an object and forms part of its total kinetic energy.}}
{{term|[[rotational speed]]}}
{{ghat|Also called '''speed of revolution'''.}}
{{defn|The number of complete rotations or revolutions a rotating body makes per unit time.}}
{{term|[[Rydberg formula]]}}
{{defn|A formula used in atomic physics to describe the wavelengths of spectral lines of many chemical elements.}}
{{glossaryend}}

