{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = Gossip from the Forest | image = File:Gossip-from-the-Forest-cover.jpg | caption = | alt = | author = [[Sara Maitland]] | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = UK | language = | series = | subject = The connections between [[forest]]s and [[fairy tale|fairytales]] in Northern Europe | genre = | published = 2012 | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = 9781847084293 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = }} '''''Gossip from the Forest: the Tangled Roots of our Forests and Fairytales''''' is a 2012 book by [[Sara Maitland]] about the connections between [[forest]]s and [[fairy tale|fairytales]] in [[Northern Europe]]. It is structured around accounts of walks through 12 forests in Scotland and England, one per month of the year, and 12 associated retellings of traditional fairytales, and was published by [[Granta]] ({{ISBN|9781847084293}}).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/28/sara-maitland-gossip-forest-review|title=Gossip from the Forest by Sara Maitland – review|last=Lang|first=Olivia|date=28 October 2012|work=[[The Observer]]|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/paperback-review-gossip-from-the-forest-by-sarah-maitland-8640735.html|title=Paperback review: Gossip from the Forest, By Sarah Maitland|last=McDowell|first=Leslie|date=1 June 2013|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jun/21/gossip-from-forest-maitland-review|title=Gossip from the Forest by Sara Maitland – review|last=Segal|first=Victoria|date=21 June 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>
Maitland has described the book as "a hybrid book ... history and photographs and nature and politics and science and anthropology and fiction (my own retellings of 12 Grimm stories) and, indeed, gossip."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/nov/14/sara-maitland-top-10-books-forests?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487|title=Sara Maitland's top 10 books of the forest|date=14 November 2012|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>
==The chapters: the forests and the retold tales== [[File:Bremen.band.500pix.jpg|right|The Four Comrades / Town Musicians of Bremen, statue in Bremen|thumb]] *March :*Airyolland Wood, [[Dumfries and Galloway]] <!-- page 1 --> :*"[[Thumbling]]" *April :*Saltridge Wood, near [[Stroud]], Gloucestershire <!-- page 35 --> :*"[[The White Snake]]" *May :*[[New Forest|The New Forest]], Hampshire :*"[[Rumpelstiltskin]]" *June :*[[Epping Forest]], Greater London and Essex :*"[[Hansel and Gretel]]" *July :*The Great North Wood, [[Dulwich]], [[Sydenham]] and [[West Norwood|Norwood]], London <!-- page 122 --> :*"Little Goosegirl" *August :*Staverton Thicks (and Staverton Park), [[Suffolk]] :*"The Seven Swans' Sister" - see "[[The Six Swans]]" *September :*[[Forest of Dean]], Gloucestershire :*"[[The Seven Dwarves]]" *October :*[[Ballochbuie]], near [[Braemar]] and the [[Mar Lodge Estate|Forest of Mar]], Aberdeenshire <!-- page 211 --> :*"[[Rapunzel]]" *November :*[[Kielder Forest]], Northumberland :*"[[Little Red Riding Hood|Little Red Riding Hood and the Big Bad Wolf]]" *December :* The Purgatory Wood, near [[New Luce]], Dumfries and Galloway <!-- page 255 --> :*"The Four Comrades" - see "[[Town Musicians of Bremen]]" *January :*[[Glenlee, Dumfries and Galloway|Glenlee]]: woods at this house near [[New Galloway]], Dumfries and Galloway <!-- page 280 --> :*"Dancing Shoes" - see "[[The Twelve Dancing Princesses]]" *February :*Knockman Wood, [[River Cree|Cree Valley]], [[Galloway Hills]] <!-- page 312 --> :*"The Dreams of the [[Sleeping Beauty]]"
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:British non-fiction books]] [[Category:Works about fairy tales]] [[Category:Natural history books]] [[Category:Anthropology books]] [[Category:2012 non-fiction books]] [[Category:English non-fiction books]] [[Category:Books about cats]] [[Category:Dogs in literature]] {{anthropology-book-stub}}

{{Linguistics}}

'''Graphetics''' is a branch of [[linguistics]] concerned with the analysis of the physical properties of shapes used in [[writing]].<ref name="Crystal2003">{{cite encyclopedia | title=Graphetics | encyclopedia=Dictionary of Linguistics and Phonetics | publisher=Blackwell | accessdate=October 10, 2011 | author=Crystal, David | year=2003 | edition=5th | location=Malden, MA | isbn=978-0-631-22663-5 | series=The Language Library | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3JtAOHLtlHoC&pg=PA210#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref name="Blackwell1999">{{cite encyclopedia | title=Graphetics | encyclopedia=The Blackwell Encyclopedia of Writing Systems | publisher=Blackwell | accessdate=October 10, 2011 | editor=Coulmas, Florian | year=1999 | location=Blackwell Reference Online | url=http://www.blackwellreference.com/public/tocnode?id=g9780631214816_chunk_g97806312148169_ss1-18}}</ref> 

It is an [[etic]] study, meaning that it has an outsider's perspective and is not concerned with any particular writing system. It is contrasted with the related [[emic]] field of [[graphemics]], the study of the relation between different shapes in particular writing systems.<ref name="Crystal2003" /> Graphetics is analogous to [[phonetics]]; graphetics is to the study of writing as phonetics is to the study of [[spoken language]]. As such, it can be divided into two areas, ''visual graphetics'' and ''mechanical graphetics'', which are analogous to [[auditory phonetics|auditory]] and [[articulatory phonetics|articulatory]] phonetics, respectively.<ref name="Blackwell1999" /> Both [[printing|printed]] and [[handwriting|handwritten]] language can be the subject of graphetic study.<ref name="Hartmann1998">{{cite encyclopedia | title=Graphetics | encyclopedia=Dictionary of Lexicography | publisher=Routledge | accessdate=October 10, 2011 | author=Hartmann, R. R. K. | year=1998 | location=London, New York | isbn=978-0-415-14143-7 | author2=James, Gregory | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=49NZ12icE-QC&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>

