{{Linguistics-stub}}

{{Orphan|date=June 2016}}
{{Infobox scientist | name = Katrin Linse | image = PEN 6869.jpg | caption = Katrin Linse aboard the [[RRS James Cook]] | birth_name = | nationality = [[Germany]] | fields = [[Marine biology]] | workplaces = [[British Antarctic Survey]] | alma_mater = [[University of Hamburg]] | website = [https://www.bas.ac.uk/profile/kl/ Katrin Linse at the British Antarctic Survey] }}
'''Katrin Linse''' is a German [[Antarctic]] marine biologist, best known for her work on discovering new Antarctic and deep sea species.
==Early life and education== Linse was born in Germany.<ref name="Classroom@Sea » Meet the Team">{{Cite web|url=http://www.classroomatsea.net/JC042/JC042team|title=Meet the Team|website=www.classroomatsea.net|publisher=Classroom@Sea|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref> She discovered marine biology at the age of six, thanks to undergraduates she encountered while on holiday with her family. She developed the goal of working in polar science at the age of twelve, when a national polar research vessel was being built in a shipyard near to her family home: forbidden from visiting the shipyard during its open day, a were all women and children, Linse announced that one day she would sail aboard the ship to study marine life in the Antarctic. At the age of twenty-six, she did so for the first time.<ref name="cambridge-news.co.uk">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/biologist-katrin-linse-went-dissecting-starfish/story-29056103-detail/story.html|title=How biologist Katrin Linse went from dissecting starfish on the beach to sailing to Antarctica|date=2016-04-06|website=Cambridge News|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref>
Linse received her undergraduate degree with ''magna cum laude'' honors from [[University of Kiel|Kiel University]], where she also completed her master's degree. She completed her PhD at the [[University of Hamburg]] and the Zoology Museum, where she compared molluscs collected from the tip of South America with those found in Antarctica.<ref name="Classroom@Sea » Meet the Team"/>
==Career and impact== Linse is a Senior Biodiversity Biologist at the [[British Antarctic Survey]], where she began her career in 2001.<ref name=":0"/> She is a distinguished marine benthic biologist with over fifteen years’ research experience in the biodiversity, phylogeography and evolution of Antarctic marine invertebrates.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bas.ac.uk/profile/kl/#publications|title=Katrin Linse|website=www.bas.ac.uk|publisher=British Antarctic Survey|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref> She has participated in over 13 ship-based expeditions, including several that studied hydrothermal habitats in the [[Southern Ocean]] and numerous that have impacted global knowledge of the Southern Ocean and Antarctica. She has led or contributed to the discovery of dozens of new species, as she works toward what she has referred to as a “census of marine life in the Southern Ocean.”<ref name="cambridge-news.co.uk"/><ref name=":0" />
Among Linse’s contributions to Antarctic science is her work leading the team that designed the first georeferenced Antarctic benthos database, which resulted in new Antarctic provinces and an updated biogeography for the Southern Ocean. Her research on phylogenetic relationships of current Antarctic species and their evolutionary histories contributed to the discovery of high biodiversity in the bathyal and abyssal Antarctic deep sea,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenakedscientists.com/HTML/interviews/interview/1928/|title=New Species At Hydrothermal Vents - Planet Earth Online - Katrin Linse And Ali Graham, British Antarctic Survey - The Naked Scientists|website=www.thenakedscientists.com|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qualitymarine.com/Weird-New-Animals-From-Antarctica's-Deep-Seas-(05/21/07)|title=Weird New Animals From Antarctica's Deep Seas (05/21/07) / Industry News - Quality Marine|website=www.qualitymarine.com|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref> and influenced the discovery of the first hydrothermal vents in the Southern Ocean. She also has led or contributed to numerous teams that discovered new species, including a new family of deep-sea starfish living in the warm waters around a hydrothermal vent in the [[East Scotia Ridge]] in the Southern Ocean; a new species of bug (''[[Jaera tyleri]])'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bas.ac.uk/media-post/new-critter-discovered-on-whale-carcass/|title=NEWS STORY: New critter discovered on whale carcass - News - British Antarctic Survey|website=www.bas.ac.uk|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref> similar in appearance to the common woodlouse, which was found plastered all over a whale carcass on the floor of the deep Southern Ocean; and more than thirty new species of marine life discovered during an expedition to the [[Amundsen Sea]] off Pine Island Bay in Antarctica. She also was part of the BAS team that made the first comprehensive “inventory” of sea and land animals around a group of Antarctic islands, [[South Orkney Islands]], near the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bas.ac.uk/media-post/first-comprehensive-inventory-of-life-in-antarctica/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Continent’s diversity revealed - News - British Antarctic Survey|website=www.bas.ac.uk|access-date=2016-06-18}}</ref>
